Ford GoBike Dataset Exploration¶

by Mohammed Ezzat Yassin¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

Bay Wheels (formerly Ford GoBike) is the Bay Area’s premier bikeshare system, and one of the largest in the nation. Get access to thousands of bikes and see public transit schedules around you in San Francisco, Oakland, Berkeley, Emeryville, and San Jose. Best of all, it’s available 24/7.

Bay Wheels consists of a fleet of specially-designed, sturdy, and durable electric bikes that can be accessed throughout the Bay Area, as well as classic bikes that are locked into a network of docking stations in Bay Area cities.The bikes can be unlocked from one station and returned to any other station in the system, making them ideal for one-way trips.

This data set includes information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area in feb, 2019.

Quality issues¶

1- The start_time, end_times, user_type, and member_gender columns are object type.

2- The start_station_id, end_station_id, and member_birth_year columns are float.

3- The bike_id column is integer

Tidiness issues¶

1- The member_birth_year column doesn't represent the age of members correctly.

2- start_time and end_times containg information about the month, day and hour of the trips but in very confusing way.

3- start_station_latitude, start_station_longitude, end_station_latitude, and end_station_longitude columns contain information about the position of the start and end stations in inappropriate way.

4- There is no columns represnts the velocity of trips.

5- The duration of trips in seconds may be confused.

Data Cleaning¶

#Perform some wrangling
#Change the start_time and end_time columns to date type
fordgobike['start_time'] = pd.to_datetime(fordgobike['start_time'])
fordgobike['end_time'] = pd.to_datetime(fordgobike['end_time'])

#Change the user_type and member_gender columns to category type
fordgobike['user_type'] = fordgobike['user_type'].astype('category')
fordgobike['member_gender'] = fordgobike['member_gender'].astype('category')

#convert the start_station_id, end_station_id and bike_id columns to string
fordgobike['start_station_id'] = fordgobike['start_station_id'].astype(str)
fordgobike['end_station_id'] = fordgobike['end_station_id'].astype(str)
fordgobike['bike_id'] = fordgobike['bike_id'].astype(str)
In [8]:
#Calculate the distances in meters between the start and end stations
from geopy.distance import geodesic

#Create a function to calculate the distances from the lattitude and longitude of stations
def distance_calc (row):
    """
    Calculate the distance between two points using the lattitude and longitude .

    Args:
        row: the latitude and longitude of the start and stop stations are obtained by the read function row. 
    Returns:
        The distance between the start and stop stations in meters is calculated using geodesic function.
    """
    start = (row['start_station_latitude'], row['start_station_longitude'])
    stop = (row['end_station_latitude'], row['end_station_longitude'])

    return geodesic(start, stop).meters

#create calc_dist column to store the calculated distances
fordgobike['calc_dist'] = fordgobike.apply (lambda row: distance_calc (row),axis=1)
In [9]:
#change the duration time to float and the convert the unit to minute
fordgobike['duration_min'] = fordgobike['duration_sec'] / 60

#create velocity in meter per seconds column of each trip
fordgobike['velocity'] = fordgobike['calc_dist'] / fordgobike['duration_sec']

#create columns for trip start date in yyyy-mm-dd format, trip start hour of the day, day of week
fordgobike['start_date'] = fordgobike.start_time.dt.strftime('%Y-%m-%d')
fordgobike['start_hour_ofday'] = fordgobike.start_time.dt.strftime('%H')
fordgobike['start_day_ofweek'] = fordgobike.start_time.dt.strftime('%A')

#Create a column for the age of riders
fordgobike['member_age'] = 2019 - fordgobike['member_birth_year']
In [10]:
#create a column for the day of week to be categories into weekend or work days
fordgobike['WEEKDAY'] = pd.to_datetime(fordgobike['start_time']).dt.dayofweek 
fordgobike['day_type'] = 0          
fordgobike.loc[fordgobike['WEEKDAY'].isin([5, 6]), 'day_type'] = 'weekend'  # 5 and 6 correspond to Sat and Sun
fordgobike.loc[fordgobike['WEEKDAY'].isin([0, 1, 2, 3, 4]), 'day_type'] = 'work_days'
fordgobike['day_type'] = fordgobike['day_type'].astype('category')

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 183412 trips in the dataset with information about the timing of trips (start time, end time and duration in seconds), start stations (id, name, latitude and longitude), end stations (id, name, latitude and longitude), bike id, the user type (customer or Subscriber), the members (gender and birth date) and bike share for all trip which tracks members who are enrolled in the Bike Share for All program for low-income residents.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm most interested in figuring out:

1- The growth of the company on the basis of the number of trips, duration of trips and nummber of subscribers.

2- The peak hours, day of weeks and month of the trips to figure out the rush times.

3- The characterstics asscociated with riders with duration trips above the average to figure out the main target customers.

4- The most common stations used as start or end.

5- The average distance of the most trips.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

The characterstics of the customers (gender, type and age) will help to figure out the main target customers. Also, the hours, day of week and month of the most trips are help to figure out the patterns to determine the rush hours.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

unusual distributions¶

1- The number of trips by women are very small compared to trips of men. A further analysis should be done to explore the reasons and the characterstics of women's trips to dicover the method of encouraging them for more trips

2- The number of trips at the week end is smaller than working days. the charcterstics of weekend trips should be explored.

3- There is more than 2000 trips with zero distance i.e, started and ended at the same station. A further analysis should be done to explore those characterstics.

Cleaning Process¶

1- Convert the data types of some columns such as start_time, end_times, user_type, and member_gender.

2- Create a distance of trips column from the longitude and lattitude of the start and end stations. Then, create create a velocity of trips column from the distance and time columns.

3- Extract the hour per day and day of week fromthe start time column.

4- Delete the unused columns.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

Generally, There are more men than women using the service. But, The riding habit/pattern of women shows that they are use the service above 10 minutes in duration and over than 1 kilometer in distance with lower average velocity than men. The age of women using the service is slightly lower than men. The pattern of women trips shows also that the ratio of trips at weekkend to the total week days is higher for women than men which indicates that women perfer to use the service as a picnic than work transportation.

The weekends have lower number of trips than work days. But, The weekend riding pattern shows that a higher duration and distance and acquire the most of zero-distance trips with a riders age is lower than the work days.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

The multivariate exploration strengthened some of the patterns discovered in the previous bivariate exploration as well as univariate exploration:

1- Although men are represents 75% of the reiders and consequently have larger numer of trips than women, but women have average trips distance and duration larger than men especially at weekends. This pattern shows that women doesn't prefer using the service for work transportation than Exercising out of work times, this may be beacause of the physical exertion of bike riding or women work dressing style which doesn't convenient with bike pedaling. So that, ebikes those taking some of the effort out of pedaling will be an apporiate solution to increase the number of women riders.

2- The number of trips show that the work days obsesse the most trips beacasue that the service is mainly used for work transportation especially at the ruch hours of going to (07, 08, 09) and from work (16, 17, 18). While, the duration of trips show that the trips at weekends have a much higher average durations for the younger and older riders. Also, the customers have constant usage of the service along the week days which reflects that at weekend at which the suscribers have a low service usage, the customers have an average duration of trips higher than the suscribers. So that, the company should creates a special package for the weekend riding which will encourage much people whose prefer using the bikes as Exercising rather than work transportation to use the services.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

Older riders (50 - 65) have the longest average trip durations.
